Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for your rice. Once the water is
rapidly boiling add the @Basmati rice{1}. Cook for around ~{25%minutes} or until
soft enough to eat. Drain the rice and place back in the pot with a cloth over
it until you are ready to eat.

Chop the @British chicken thighs{3} into bite-sized chunks. Peel and finely dice
both the @red onion{1/2}(peeled and finely diced) and the @garlic clove{1}(peeled
and finely diced). Slice the @red chilli{1} in half and dice as much as you want
in your curry.

> The spice mix is already slightly hot so go careful if you like it mild.

Using the edge of a #spoon{} peel the skin from the @ginger{1}. Dice the ginger
very finely.

Heat @oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on high heat. Toss the chicken pieces
in a #bowl{} with the @cornflour{1} and a good pinch of @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Once the oil is really hot, gently add the chicken into the pan (it'll
sputter a bit). Cook for a few minutes until golden brown then remove from the
pan.

Turn the heat down to medium-low and add another @oil{1/2%tbsp}. Add the onion,
garlic, chilli and ginger and cook gently for ~{5%minutes}.

> Make sure you do not burn the ingredients - if they are getting too hot add 1
> tbsp of cold water and turn the heat down.

Add the @Tandoori Masala Spice{1} to the onion mix and cook for a further
~{1%minute}. Next add the @chopped tomatoes{1} with @sugar{1/4%tsp} and
@salt{1/4%tsp}. Add the chicken back into the pan. Turn the heat to low and let
the mixture gently bubble until slightly thicker.

Once the sauce has thickened, add 2/3 of @Greek style natural yoghurt{3} and stir.
Leave to bubble gently for ~{5%minutes} before adding a few tbsp of
@coriander{3}(chopped) to the mix.

Serve the curry with your rice and a sprinkle of chopped coriander. Ta-daaa!